{
  "text": "Finishing steers in meadows after they had received a high-feeding level during the winter period is a feasible system in dry mountain areas, but it causes the scarcity of carcass fatness [CITATION_1] . A narrow subcutaneous fat cover can have a negative impact on meat quality due to the cold shortening [CITATION_2] . Therefore, a finishing period would be advisable in order to improve carcass quality. Cattle are usually finished on concentrates after grazing, which improves subcutaneous fat [CITATION_3] , but may change meat quality. If cattle were finished with a high-forage total mixed ration, however, carcass fatness could be improved without an increase of the use of cereals on-farm. The aim of this study was to analyse the performances and carcass quality of steers slaughtered from pasture and steers finished with a total-mixed ration after grazing, and then compare them with the control, concentrate-fed young bulls.",
